======================================================================
PART 1: THE f(n) = T(m) EQUATION ‚ÄĒ FULL ANALYSIS
======================================================================

Searching for f(n) = T(m):

  T(1) = 1: 4¬∑1+1 = 5, ‚ąö=2.2361 NOT perfect square
  T(2) = 1: 4¬∑1+1 = 5, ‚ąö=2.2361 NOT perfect square
  T(3) = 2: 4¬∑2+1 = 9 = 3¬≤, n = 4 or 1
    f(4) = (4-2)(4-3) = 2¬∑1 = 2
    f(1) = (1-2)(1-3) = -1¬∑-2 = 2
  T(4) = 4: 4¬∑4+1 = 17, ‚ąö=4.1231 NOT perfect square
  T(5) = 12: 4¬∑12+1 = 49 = 7¬≤, n = 6 or -1
    f(6) = (6-2)(6-3) = 4¬∑3 = 12
  T(6) = 56: 4¬∑56+1 = 225 = 15¬≤, n = 10 or -5
    f(10) = (10-2)(10-3) = 8¬∑7 = 56
  T(7) = 456: 4¬∑456+1 = 1825, ‚ąö=42.7200 NOT perfect square
  T(8) = 6880: 4¬∑6880+1 = 27521, ‚ąö=165.8945 NOT perfect square

SUMMARY: f(n) = T(m) has solutions:
  n=1: f(1) = (-1)¬∑(-2) = 2 = T(3)
  n=4: f(4) = 2¬∑1 = 2 = T(3)
  n=6: f(6) = 4¬∑3 = 12 = T(5)
  n=10: f(10) = 8¬∑7 = 56 = T(6)

The f-T bridge values:
  n=4:  4 = KEY‚āĀ¬≤ ‚Üí T(KEY‚āā) = T(3) = 2
  n=6:  6 = KEY‚āĀ¬∑KEY‚āā ‚Üí T(KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā) = T(5) = 12
  n=10: 10 = KEY‚āĀ¬∑(KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā) ‚Üí T(KEY‚āĀ¬∑KEY‚āā) = T(6) = 56

Algebraic pattern:
  n = KEY‚āĀ¬∑a ‚Üí T(b)
  (a, b) pairs: (2, 3), (3, 5), (5, 6)

  Observation: the a-values are 2, 3, 5 = the tournament primes!
  And the b-values are: 3=a‚āĀ+1, 5=a‚āā+2, 6=a‚āÉ+1

Pattern through f(2k) = 2(k-1)(2k-3):
  k= 1: f(2) = 2¬∑0¬∑-1 = 0
  k= 2: f(4) = 2¬∑1¬∑1 = 2 = T(3)
  k= 3: f(6) = 2¬∑2¬∑3 = 12 = T(5)
  k= 4: f(8) = 2¬∑3¬∑5 = 30
  k= 5: f(10) = 2¬∑4¬∑7 = 56 = T(6)
  k= 6: f(12) = 2¬∑5¬∑9 = 90
  k= 7: f(14) = 2¬∑6¬∑11 = 132
  k= 8: f(16) = 2¬∑7¬∑13 = 182
  k= 9: f(18) = 2¬∑8¬∑15 = 240
  k=10: f(20) = 2¬∑9¬∑17 = 306
  k=11: f(22) = 2¬∑10¬∑19 = 380
  k=12: f(24) = 2¬∑11¬∑21 = 462
  k=13: f(26) = 2¬∑12¬∑23 = 552
  k=14: f(28) = 2¬∑13¬∑25 = 650

f(2k) = T(m) at k ‚ąą {2, 3, 5} ‚ÄĒ the tournament primes!
  k=KEY‚āĀ: f(2¬∑KEY‚āĀ) = T(KEY‚āā)
  k=KEY‚āā: f(2¬∑KEY‚āā) = T(KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā)
  k=KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā: f(2¬∑(KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā)) = T(KEY‚āĀ¬∑KEY‚āā)

