PART 3: THE n=9 TRANSITION ‚ÄĒ PETERSEN MINUS ONE
======================================================================

n=9 as Petersen-1:
  9 = 10-1 = (Petersen vertices) - 1
  9 = KEY‚āā¬≤ = 3¬≤
  C(9,2) = 36 = 6¬≤ = (KEY‚āĀ¬∑KEY‚āā)¬≤
  C(10,2) - C(9,2) = 45-36 = 9 = KEY‚āā¬≤
  Adding the 10th vertex adds 9 new edges!

Transition 9‚Üí10:
  New arcs: 9 = KEY‚āā¬≤
  New arc orientations: 2‚ĀĻ = 512 = KEY‚āĀ^KEY‚āā¬≤
  T(10)/T(9) = ?/?

n=9 as 3√ó3:
  9 = 3√ó3 ‚Üí arrange in a 3√ó3 grid
  Row tournaments: 3 rows of 3-tournaments
  Column tournaments: 3 columns of 3-tournaments
  Each row/column has 2 possible tournament types
  Row/column interaction: 9 inter-row edges per pair

Latin square connection:
  3√ó3 Latin squares: 12 = T(5) = h(E‚āÜ)
  (There are 12 reduced 3√ó3 Latin squares)
  This matches T(5)! Coincidence or structure?

Verification: T(5) = 12
  Non-isomorphic tournaments on 5 vertices:
  1. Transitive T‚āÖ
  2-12. Various non-transitive ones
  (There are exactly 3 regular tournaments on 5)

======================================================================
PART 4: THE INDEPENDENCE POLYNOMIAL CASCADE
======================================================================

Petersen independence polynomial:
  I(P, x) = 1x^0 + 10x^1 + 30x^2 + 30x^3 + 5x^4

  Coefficients: {alpha_P}
  őĪ‚āĀ = 10 = #vertices
  őĪ‚āā = 30 = h(E‚āą) = #complement edges
  őĪ‚āÉ = 30 = h(E‚āą) again!
  őĪ‚āĄ = 5 = KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā = #max independent sets

STRIKING: őĪ‚āā = őĪ‚āÉ = 30 = h(E‚āą)
  The Petersen graph has EQUAL numbers of independent pairs and triples!
  This is related to the Petersen graph being 'almost self-complementary'

  őĪ‚āā = #edges of complement = 30 ‚úď
  őĪ‚āÉ = #independent triples = #triangles of complement
  So the complement J(5,2) has exactly 30 edges AND 30 triangles!

  Triangles in J(5,2) = L(K‚āÖ):
    Type A (star): 5 ¬∑ C(4,3) = 5 ¬∑ 4 = 20
    Type B (triangle): C(5,3) = 10
    Total: 20 + 10 = 30 = h(E‚āą) ‚úď

I(P, x) at special values:
  I(P, -2) =    -59 = I(-KEY‚āĀ)
  I(P, -1) =     -4 = Euler char of indep complex
  I(P,  0) =      1
  I(P,  1) =     76
  I(P,  2) =    461 = H if Petersen were CG
  I(P,  3) =   1516 = I(KEY‚āā)
  I(P,  4) =   3721
  I(P,  5) =   7676

  I(P, -1) = -4 < 0 ‚Č§ 1
  If Petersen were CG(T), we'd need I(-1) ‚Č§ 1
  -4 ‚Č§ 1 ‚úď so the bound is satisfied
  But is -4 achievable? Is Petersen realizable as CG?

