======================================================================
PART 6: THE PETERSEN GRAPH AS ADE BOUNDARY
======================================================================

BOUNDARY PHENOMENA:

1. ADE classification boundary:
   (2,3,5) ‚Üí E‚āą is the LAST exceptional
   1/2+1/3+1/5 > 1 (spherical)
   1/2+1/3+1/7 < 1 (hyperbolic, no exceptional)

2. Petersen graph uniqueness:
   K(5,2) is the smallest triangle-free graph with Ōá=3
   It's the 'worst case' for many graph theory conjectures
   Every counterexample to optimistic conjectures involves Petersen

3. Tournament moat at n=10:
   T(10) ‚Čą 10‚Ā∑ ‚ÄĒ first time T(n) > n!
   At n=10, symmetry-breaking dominates
   2^C(10,2)/10! = 2^45/10! ‚Čą T(10)

T(n) vs n!:
  T( 1) =            1, 1! =          1  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 2) =            1, 2! =          2  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 3) =            2, 3! =          6  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 4) =            4, 4! =         24  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 5) =           12, 5! =        120  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 6) =           56, 6! =        720  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 7) =          456, 7! =       5040  T ‚Č§ n!
  T( 8) =         6880, 8! =      40320  T ‚Č§ n!

T(n) first exceeds n! at n=10 = Petersen vertex count!
This is the MOAT: beyond n=10, tournament enumeration
surpasses factorial growth.

======================================================================
PART 7: THE 5-REGULARITY AND EXCEPTIONAL GROUPS
======================================================================

THE FIVE-FOLD SYMMETRY:

In the Petersen graph:
  - Built from 5-element set (Kneser K(5,2))
  - Girth 5
  - 5 maximum independent sets
  - 5 complementary pairs
  - Automorphism group acts on 5 elements (S‚āÖ)

In exceptional Lie theory:
  - 5 exceptional simple Lie algebras
  - 5 = KEY‚āĀ+KEY‚āā = third tournament prime
  - E‚āą branch lengths: 2+3+5 = 10 (sum = 2¬∑5)
  - Product: 2¬∑3¬∑5 = 30 = h(E‚āą)

In Platonic solids:
  - 5 Platonic solids
  - Icosahedron: 12 vertices, 30 edges, 20 faces
  - Dodecahedron: 20 vertices, 30 edges, 12 faces
  - Both have 30 = h(E‚āą) edges!

THE 30-EDGE TRINITY:
  Icosahedron:        30 edges
  Dodecahedron:       30 edges
  Petersen complement: 30 edges
  All equal h(E‚āą) = 30!

  The Petersen complement = L(K‚āÖ) = J(5,2)
  This is a 6-regular graph on 10 vertices with 30 edges
  The icosahedron is a 5-regular graph on 12 vertices with 30 edges
  The dodecahedron is a 3-regular graph on 20 vertices with 30 edges

Euler characteristic check (V-E+F=2 for polyhedra):
  Icosahedron: 12-30+20 = 2
  Dodecahedron: 20-30+12 = 2
  J(5,2) = L(K‚āÖ): not planar (contains K‚āÖ as minor)

